<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="41.[189,454,396,422]" box="[189,454,396,422]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,454,396,422]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,454,396,422]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Differential diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[189,1399,441,535]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
The character combination of protruded face, presence of distinct baso-lateral spur on fore coxa, broad parafacia and very characteristic structure of male genitalia separates 
<taxonomicName authority="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls, 2022" authorityName="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls" authorityYear="2022" box="[1047,1398,474,501]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Cheilosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falcata" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Cheilosia">
<emphasis box="[1047,1162,474,500]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Cheilosia</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1180,1295,474,500]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Cheilosia</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1315,1398,474,500]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">falcata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[189,280,509,535]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
from all congeners. See also under 
<taxonomicName authority="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls, 2022" authorityName="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls" authorityYear="2022" box="[699,1049,508,534]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Cheilosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosa" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Cheilosia">
<emphasis box="[699,811,508,534]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Cheilosia</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[829,941,508,534]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Cheilosia</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[959,1049,509,534]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">spinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1056,1146,509,535]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[189,1399,572,643]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="41.[189,324,572,598]" box="[189,324,572,598]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,572,598]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,572,598]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[189,1399,617,643]" box="[189,1399,617,643]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
The specific epithet is from the Latin ‘ 
<emphasis box="[633,726,617,643]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">falcatus</emphasis>
’ meaning ‘sickle-shaped’ and refers to the facial tubercle.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
